<p>In the <a href="https://www.pme-math.org/journal/issues/PMEJ.Vol.2.No.6.pdf#page=18">Spring 1957 issue</a> of <em>Pi Mu Epsilon Journal</em>, C.W. Trigg points out that, by two continuous cuts, the surface of a cube can be divided into two pieces that can be unfolded and assembled into a hollow square:</p>
<figure id="attachment_71850" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-71850" style="width: 626px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/2025-10-04-piecework.png" alt="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Cube-h.svg" width="626" height="681" class="size-full wp-image-71850" srcset="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/2025-10-04-piecework.png 626w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/2025-10-04-piecework-600x653.png 600w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/10/2025-10-04-piecework-300x326.png 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 626px) 100vw, 626px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-71850" class="wp-caption-text">Image: <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Cube-h.svg">Wikimedia Commons</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>The cuts divide the cube&#8217;s surface into two congruent pieces, each composed of six connected isosceles right triangles. Joining these two pieces forms a hollow square with exterior side <span style="vertical-align:-30%;"><img decoding="async" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=++2%5Csqrt%7B2%7Dx+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002" alt="  2&#92;sqrt{2}x " class="latex" /></span> and interior side <span style="vertical-align:-30%;"><img decoding="async" src="https://s0.wp.com/latex.php?latex=+%5Csqrt%7B2%7Dx+&#038;bg=ffffff&#038;fg=000&#038;s=0&#038;c=20201002" alt=" &#92;sqrt{2}x " class="latex" /></span>, where <em>x</em> is the length of the cube&#8217;s edge.</p>
